ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 17 Apr 2016
From: J Brenner <brennerjacovet@gmail.com> [edited]


Preliminary report of serosurvey for circulation of viruses of the Simbu serogroup in dairy cattle in Israel, 2014
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Akabane virus (AKAV) was identified in 1975 as the causative agent responsible for a major outbreak of arthrogryposis-hydranencephaly [A-H] which had affected foeti of cattle, sheep, and goats in Israel in 1969/1970. In 2001, serological evidence indicated the presence in Israel of another member of the serogroup Simbu in the genus _Orthobunyavirus_, namely the Aino virus (AINOV) (Ref 1). Another member of the group, the Shuni virus (SHUV) was isolated In Nov 2014 in northern Israel from the brain and placenta of a malformed lamb and confirmed by PCR in 7 others (Ref 2).

Subsequently, a serosurvey has been conducted cooperatively by the Kimron Veterinary Institute (KVI) (J Brenner) and the National Institute of Animal Health (NIAH), Japan (T Yanase, T Kato, and T Tsuda), to screen the possible presence of other Simbu serogroup viruses in Israel.

A total of 13 dairy cattle farms in 5 districts, hotspots for _Culicoides_ activity, have been chosen. At each location, 10 adult cows and 5 heifers were sampled between July and August 2014. All sampled heifers were born after October 2013. One sheep farm was included in the survey; in this flock, Shuni virus (SHUV) had been identified by virus isolation in 2014 and by PCR in 2015 (Ref 2).

Tested at the department of Virology, KVI, all 140 adult cows were found positive by 'commercial SBV ELISA test'. (The Schmallenberg Virus Antibody Test Kit IDEXX Schmallenberg Ab; 3097 Liebefeld-Bern, Switzerland) at the 1st sampling; these adult cows were not resampled. All 75 sampled heifers were found negative at the 1st sampling. All were resampled between July and August 2014. Seroconversion was recorded in all 75 heifers.

Sera of 58 ELISA-positive bovines (19 cows and 39 heifers) and 5 (Elisa positive!) sheep were sent to the NIAH and were tested there against 5 Simbu serogroup viruses by neutralization tests. We regard cow sera as representing a cumulative history of exposure, whereas the potential exposure of heifers took place during the summer/autumn of 2014.

Sera from heifers neutralized AINOV (23/40), AKAV (13/39), Sathuperi virus (SATV) (15/40), or Shamonda virus (SHAV), (4/39), but not Peaton virus (PEAV). 7 of the heifer sera neutralized more than one single virus, whereas 6 sera did not neutralize any, despite being found positive by the commercial SBV ELISA test.

Sera from cows neutralized AINOV, AKAV, SATV, SHAV and PEAV. Up to 4 different specific antibodies were detected in some sera. PEAV antibodies were detected in 2 cows, but not in any heifer, indicating that PEAV had circulated in Israel but not in the 2014 vector season. Sera from the adult sheep neutralized AKAV, SATV, and SHAV (no test for SHUV was performed).

The findings suggest that several Simbu serogroup viruses have circulated in Israel in the past years and that multiple viruses were circulating in Israel simultaneously in the 2014 season. This survey identifies for the 1st time possible activity of SATV, SHAV, and PEAV in Israel.

References
----------
1. Brenner J, Tsuda T, Yadin H, Kato T: Serological evidence of Akabane virus infection in northern Israel in 2001. J Vet Med Sci. 2004; 66(4): 441-3. Abstract available at http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15133276.
2. Golender N, Brenner J, Valdman M et al: Malformations Caused by Shuni Virus in Ruminants, Israel, 2014-2015. Emerg Infect Dis. 2015; 21(12): 2267-8. Available at http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4672418/.

