[The preliminary findings above, indicating the circulation of several Simbu serogroup viruses in Israel, deserve the attention of other Middle East as well as European countries.

Two members of the Simbu serogroup in the genus _Orthobunyavirus_ are known to have caused large-scale outbreaks of arthrogryposis-hydranencephaly [A-H] in domestic ruminants in the Middle East (Akabane virus, since 1969) and Europe (Schmallenberg virus, since 2011). This is indicative of the presence, in these regions, of arthropod vectors which could potentially transmit and disseminate other Simbu serogroup viruses. Teratogenic capacity of the added viruses is suspected but yet to be determined for each of them.

Israel suffered its 1st and by-far largest A-H epizootic in cattle, sheep and goats during 1969/70, affecting thousands of animals, mainly in the northern districts, causing heavy economical losses and suffering. The viral, vector-borne etiology of the syndrome was suspected from its early stages, based upon epidemiological assessment and non-specific immunological findings by the Kimron Veterinary Institute (KVI), namely high levels of immunoglobulins in the pre-colostral sera of affected calves. However final diagnosis could become feasible only when the enigmatic etiology of ruminant A-H in Japan and Australia was deciphered in 1973.

In 1974, the virological department of the KVI received from Dr Y Inaba, NIAH, Tokyo, Japan, the strain JaGAr 39 of the Akabane virus for neutralization tests. A retrospective examination of the pre-colostral sera from the epizootic, which were kept frozen since the outbreak 4 years earlier, revealed antibodies to the Akabane virus. The diagnosis was supported by the testing of sera collected in 1975 from hundreds of cows which had been affected in 1969/70 as well as from heifers born during later years. All the younger animals, born after the epizootic, were negative to Akabane virus, in contrast to the high percentage of positive sera among the older cows from affected farms. Similar results were obtained in sampled sheep and goats. The said and additional data are available in the reference below.

The continuous cooperation between the KVI (Israel) and NIAH (Japan) has been indispensable, enabling the current findings as well.

Reference
---------
Kalmar E, Peleg BA, Savir D: Arthrogryposis-hydranencephaly syndrome in newborn cattle, sheep and goats -- serological survey for antibodies against the Akabane virus. Refuah Vet 1975; 32: 47-54; abstract available at https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285011413_Arthrogryposis_hydranencephaly_syndrome_in_newborn_cattle_sheep_and_goats_Serological_survey_for_antibodies_against_the_Akabane_virus.
- Mod.AS

